nWe'll also create a new config to do the Context Compaction. This **`EventsCompactionConfig`** defines two key variables:\n\n- **compaction_interval**: Asks the Runner to compact the history after every `n` conversations\n- **overlap_size**: Defines the number of previous conversations to retain for overlap\n\nWe'll then provide this app to the Runner.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Re-define our app with Events Compaction enabled\nresearch_app_compacting = App(\n    name=\"research_app_compacting\",\n    root_agent=chatbot_agent,\n    # This is the new part!\n    events_compaction_config=EventsCompactionConfig(\n        compaction_interval=3,  # Trigger compaction every 3 invocations\n        overlap_size=1,  # Keep 1 previous turn for context\n    ),\n)\n\ndb_url = \"sqlite:///my_agent_data.db\"  # Local SQLite file\nsession_service = DatabaseSessionService(db_url=db_url)\n\n# Create a new runner for our upgraded app\nresearch_runner_compacting = Runner(\n    app=research_app_compacting, session_service=session_service\n)\n\n\nprint(\"‚úÖ Research App upgraded with Events Compaction!\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-11-15T20:00:29.761230Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-11-15T20:00:29.761597Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-11-15T20:00:29.783343Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2025-11-15T20:00:29.761558Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-11-15T20:00:29.782001Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"‚úÖ Research App upgraded with Events Compaction!\n","output_type":"stream"},{"name":"stderr","text":"/tmp/ipykernel_48/3773147741.py:6: UserWarning: [EXPERIMENTAL] EventsCompactionConfig: This feature is experimental and may change or be removed in future versions without notice. It may introduce breaking changes at any time.\n  events_compaction_config=EventsCompactionConfig(\n","output_type":"stream"}],"execution_count":14},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 4.2 Running the Demo\n\nNow, let's have a conversation that is long enough to trigger the compaction. When you run the cell below, the output will look like a normal conversation. However, because we configured our `App`, a compaction process will run silently in the background after the 3rd invocation.\n\nIn the next step, we'll prove that it happened.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Turn 1\nawait run_session(\n    research_runner_compacting,\n    \"What is the latest news about AI in healthcare?\",\n    \"compaction_demo\",\n)\n\n# Turn 2\nawait run_session(\n    research_runner_compacting,\n    \"Are there any new developments in drug discovery?\",\n    \"compaction_demo\",\n)\n\n# Turn 3 - Compaction should trigger after this turn!\nawait run_session(\n    research_runner_compacting,\n    \"Tell me more about the second development you found.\",\n    \"compaction_demo\",\n)\n\n# Turn 4\nawait run_session(\n    research_runner_compacting,\n    \"Who are the main companies involved in that?\",\n    \"compaction_demo\",\n)","metadata":{"scrolled":true,"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-11-15T20:00:29.784566Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-11-15T20:00:29.785128Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-11-15T20:00:46.615006Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2025-11-15T20:00:29.785099Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-11-15T20:00:46.614092Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"\n ### Session: compaction_demo\n\nUser > What is the latest news about AI in healthcare?\ngemini-2.5-flash-lite >  The field of AI in healthcare is rapidly evolving, with new developments emerging almost daily. Here's a summary of some of the latest and most significant trends and news:\n\n**1. Advancements in Diagnostics and Imaging:**\n\n*   **AI-powered image analysis:** AI is becoming increasingly sophisticated at analyzing medical images like X-rays, CT scans, MRIs, and pathology slides. This is leading to faster and more accurate detection of diseases like cancer, diabetic retinopathy, and cardiovascular conditions. Recent news often highlights new algorithms achieving human-level or even superhuman performance in specific diagnostic tasks.\n*   **Early disease detection:** AI models are being trained to identify subtle patterns in patient data (including electronic health records, genetic information, and even wearable device data) that can predict the onset of diseases long before symptoms appear. This holds immense promise for preventative care.\n\n**2. Drug Discovery and Development:**\n\n*   **Accelerated drug design:** AI is revolutionizing drug discovery by speeding up the identification of potential drug candidates and predicting their efficacy and safety. This can significantly reduce the time and cost associated with bringing new treatments to market.\n*   **Personalized medicine:** AI is playing a crucial role in developing personalized treatment plans by analyzing a patient's unique genetic makeup, medical history, and lifestyle to predict how they will respond to different therapies.\n\n**3. AI in Clinical Decision Support:**\n\n*   **Assisting clinicians:** AI-powered tools are being integrated into electronic health record (EHR) systems to provide real-time decision support to doctors. This can help them make more informed diagnoses, recommend appropriate treatments, and identify potential drug interactions or contraindications.\n*   **Predictive analytics for patient outcomes:** AI models are being used to predict patient deterioration, hospital readmission rates, and the likelihood of developing certain complications, allowing healthcare providers to intervene proactively.\n\n**4. Generative AI and Large Language Models (LLMs) in Healthcare:**\n\n*   **Medical documentation and summarization:** LLMs are proving very effective at automating tasks like generating clinical notes, summarizing patient encounters, and drafting medical reports, freeing up clinicians' time for patient care.\n*   **Patient communication and education:** AI-powered chatbots and virtual assistants are being developed to answer patient questions, provide health information, and even offer mental health support, improving accessibility and engagement.\n*   **Medical research and knowledge synthesis:** LLMs can rapidly sift through vast amounts of medical literature to identify trends, synthesize research findings, and even help formulate new hypotheses.\n\n**5. Challenges and Ethical Considerations:**\n\n*   **Data privacy and security:** Ensuring the secure and private handling of sensitive patient data is paramount, and robust cybersecurity measures are essential.\n*   **Bias in AI algorithms:** AI models trained on biased data can perpetuate and even amplify existing health disparities. Ongoing research focuses on identifying and mitigating these biases.\n*   **Regulatory approval:** Gaining regulatory approval for AI-powered medical devices and software is a complex process, and frameworks are still evolving.\n*   **Physician adoption and trust:** Building trust among healthcare professionals and ensuring they are adequately trained to use AI tools effectively is a critical factor for widespread adoption.\n*   **Explainability and transparency:** Understanding how AI models arrive at their conclusions (explainable AI) is crucial for clinicians to trust and rely on their recommendations.\n\n**Where to find the latest news:**\n\nTo stay truly up-to-date, I'd recommend keeping an eye on:\n\n*   **Reputable medical journals:** JAMA, The Lancet, Nature Medicine, NEJM, etc.\n*   **Major tech news outlets:** TechCrunch, Wired, The Verge (often have dedicated AI sections).\n*   **Healthcare technology news sites:** Healthcare IT News, HIMSS, Becker's Hospital Review.\n*   **AI-specific news sources:** MIT Technology Review, AI News, Synced.\n*   **Company announcements:** Major tech companies (Google, Microsoft, IBM) and healthcare AI startups frequently release news about their latest breakthroughs.\n\nThe integration of AI into healthcare is not a futuristic concept; it's happening now and is poised to fundamentally reshape how we prevent, diagnose, and treat diseases.\n\n ### Session: compaction_demo\n\nUser > Are there any new developments in drug discovery?\ngemini-2.5-flash-lite >  Yes, there are constant and exciting new developments in AI-driven drug discovery! It's one of the most impactful areas where AI is making a tangible difference. Here are some of the key trends and recent advancements:\n\n**1. Generative AI for Novel Molecule Design:**\n\n*   **De Novo Design:** This is a huge area. Instead of screening existing libraries of compounds, generative AI models (like Variational Autoencoders - VAEs, Generative Adversarial Networks - GANs, and more recently, transformer-based models similar to those used in LLMs) are now capable of *designing entirely new molecules* from scratch. These models learn the complex rules of chemistry and molecular properties and can then generate molecules with desired characteristics (e.g., binding to a specific protein target, good solubility, low toxicity).\n*   **Tailored Properties:** Companies are using these generative models to create molecules optimized for specific therapeutic targets and patient populations, moving beyond just finding a \"hit\" to designing a \"best-in-class\" drug.\n\n**2. Predicting Molecular Properties and Interactions:**\n\n*   **Binding Affinity Prediction:** AI models are becoming incredibly adept at predicting how strongly a potential drug molecule will bind to its target protein. This drastically reduces the need for expensive and time-consuming lab experiments.\n*   **ADMET Prediction (Absorption, Distribution, Metabolism, Excretion, Toxicity):** Predicting how a drug will behave in the body (pharmacokinetics) and whether it will be toxic is crucial. AI is significantly improving the accuracy of these predictions early in the discovery process, helping to weed out unpromising candidates sooner.\n*   **Off-Target Effects:** AI can help identify potential unintended interactions with other biological molecules, which could lead to side effects.\n\n**3. Accelerating Target Identification:**\n\n*   **Genomics and Proteomics Analysis:** AI can sift through massive datasets of genetic and protein information to identify novel disease targets that were previously unknown or too complex to analyze manually.\n*   **Understanding Disease Pathways:** By analyzing complex biological networks, AI can help researchers understand the underlying mechanisms of diseases and pinpoint key intervention points.\n\n**4. Repurposing Existing Drugs:**\n\n*   **Finding New Uses:** AI can analyze existing drug databases and compare their molecular structures and known effects with disease profiles to identify drugs that could be repurposed for new indications. This can be a much faster and cheaper route to new treatments.\n\n**5. Optimizing Clinical Trial Design and Analysis:**\n\n*   **Patient Stratification:** AI can help identify patient subgroups most likely to respond to a particular drug, leading to more efficient and successful clinical trials.\n*   **Predicting Trial Outcomes:** AI models can analyze early-stage trial data to predict the likelihood of success in later phases.\n\n**Examples of Companies and Their Work (general trends, not specific news announcements):**\n\n*   **BenevolentAI:** Uses AI to analyze scientific literature and clinical data to identify new drug targets and accelerate drug development.\n*   **Exscientia:** Focuses on using AI to design novel drug candidates with specific properties.\n*   **Atomwise:** Employs deep learning for structure-based drug discovery, predicting how small molecules will bind to proteins.\n*   **Insilico Medicine:** A prominent player in generative AI for drug discovery, known for its end-to-end AI platform.\n*   **NVIDIA:** While a hardware company, their GPUs are essential for training AI models in drug discovery, and they offer platforms and tools to aid researchers.\n\n**Key Takeaways:**\n\n*   **Speed and Efficiency:** AI is drastically shortening the timelines for drug discovery, which traditionally can take over a decade and cost billions.\n*   **Precision and Novelty:** AI enables the design of highly specific molecules and the exploration of novel therapeutic avenues.\n*   **Reduced Failure Rates:** By improving predictions early on, AI helps reduce the high failure rates seen in drug development.\n\nThe field is still maturing, and there are ongoing challenges like data quality, model interpretability, and regulatory hurdles. However, the pace of innovation is incredible, and AI is undoubtedly transforming the landscape of pharmaceutical research and development.\n\n ### Session: compaction_demo\n\nUser > Tell me more about the second development you found.\ngemini-2.5-flash-lite >  You're asking about the second development I mentioned in the context of AI in drug discovery: **Predicting Molecular Properties and Interactions.** This is a critical area because it helps researchers understand how a potential drug will behave *before* it's synthesized and tested in costly and time-consuming laboratory experiments.\n\nHere's a deeper dive into this development:\n\n**What does \"Predicting Molecular Properties and Interactions\" actually mean?**\n\nIt refers to using AI models to forecast various characteristics of a potential drug molecule, including:\n\n*   **Binding Affinity:** This is perhaps the most fundamental prediction. It's about how strongly a drug molecule will attach itself to its intended biological target (usually a protein or enzyme involved in a disease). A strong binding affinity is often correlated with a drug's effectiveness.\n*   **Pharmacokinetics (PK) and Pharmacodynamics (PD):**\n    *   **Absorption:** How well will the drug be absorbed into the bloodstream (e.g., if taken orally)?\n    *   **Distribution:** Where will the drug go in the body? Will it reach the target tissue effectively?\n    *   **Metabolism:** How will the body break down the drug? Are the byproducts safe?\n    *   **Excretion:** How will the drug and its metabolites be eliminated from the body?\n    *   **Pharmacodynamics (PD):** What is the drug's effect on the body once it reaches its target? This is about the mechanism of action and the resulting physiological response.\n*   **Toxicity and Side Effects:** Predicting whether a drug will cause harmful effects. This is often broken down into:\n    *   **General Toxicity:** Will it damage major organs like the liver or kidneys?\n    *   **Specific Toxicities:** For example, will it cause cardiac issues (hERG channel blockage) or genotoxicity (damage to DNA)?\n    *   **Off-Target Effects:** Will the drug bind to unintended targets in the body, leading to unwanted side effects?\n*   **Solubility:** How well will the drug dissolve in water or other biological fluids? This is crucial for formulation and absorption.\n*   **Stability:** How stable is the molecule under different conditions (e.g., temperature, pH)?\n\n**How is AI used for these predictions?**\n\nAI, particularly machine learning and deep learning, excels at finding complex patterns in large datasets. In this context, the datasets consist of:\n\n1.  **Chemical Structures:** Databases of millions of known molecules.\n2.  **Biological Assays:** Results from experiments that measure binding affinity, toxicity, metabolic rates, etc., for these molecules.\n3.  **Protein Structures:** Information about the 3D shapes of target proteins.\n4.  **Genomic and Proteomic Data:** Information about the biological systems themselves.\n\nAI models (like Graph Neural Networks - GNNs, Convolutional Neural Networks - CNNs, and transformers) learn the relationships between a molecule's structure and its properties based on this historical data.\n\n*   **For Binding Affinity:** Models can learn the intricate ways a molecule interacts with the 3D structure of a target protein, predicting how well they fit together and the strength of their interaction.\n*   **For ADMET/Toxicity:** Models analyze the chemical features of a molecule that are known to be associated with good or bad absorption, metabolism, or toxicity. For example, certain functional groups might be flagged as potentially toxic.\n*   **For Solubility:** Models learn how the physical and chemical properties of a molecule (like its polarity, size, and the presence of certain functional groups) influence its solubility.\n\n**Why is this development so significant?**\n\n*   **Reduces Experimental Burden:** Before AI, researchers had to synthesize and test thousands, sometimes millions, of compounds in the lab. AI can prioritize which compounds are most promising, saving immense amounts of time, resources, and money.\n*   **Faster Drug Development Cycles:** By identifying potential issues early, AI helps avoid costly late-stage failures. A drug candidate predicted to be toxic or ineffective can be discarded much earlier in the process.\n*   **Improves Drug \"Druggability\":** AI helps design molecules that are not only effective but also have favorable pharmacological properties, making them more likely to become successful drugs.\n*   **Enables \"Design for Safety\":** By predicting potential toxicities, AI allows researchers to proactively design molecules to be safer from the outset.\n*   **Uncovers Non-Obvious Relationships:** AI can identify subtle correlations between molecular structure and biological outcomes that human researchers might miss.\n\nIn essence, predicting molecular properties and interactions allows AI to act as an incredibly powerful, virtual laboratory assistant, guiding drug discovery efforts towards the most viable candidates.\n\n ### Session: compaction_demo\n\nUser > Who are the main companies involved in that?\ngemini-2.5-flash-lite >  Several types of companies are heavily involved in leveraging AI for predicting molecular properties and interactions in drug discovery. This is a broad area, so you'll see a mix of:\n\n**1. Dedicated AI Drug Discovery Companies:**\n\nThese companies are built from the ground up with AI at their core. They often have proprietary algorithms and large datasets.\n\n*   **Exscientia:** A leader in AI-driven drug design, focusing on generating novel molecules and predicting their properties to accelerate development.\n*   **BenevolentAI:** Uses AI to mine vast amounts of scientific literature, clinical trial data, and other sources to identify new drug targets and discover potential drug candidates with favorable properties.\n*   **Atomwise:** Specializes in using deep learning (specifically convolutional neural networks) for structure-based drug discovery, predicting how small molecules will bind to proteins.\n*   **Insilico Medicine:** A major player in generative AI for drug discovery, they utilize AI for target identification, molecule generation, and prediction of properties.\n*   **Recursion Pharmaceuticals:** Combines AI and automation to map human cellular responses to diseases and drug compounds, enabling them to predict drug efficacy and toxicity.\n*   **Schr√∂dinger:** While not solely an AI company, Schr√∂dinger is a leader in computational chemistry and physics-based drug design, and they heavily integrate AI and machine learning into their platforms for predicting molecular properties.\n*   **Valo Health:** Focuses on building an integrated AI-powered platform that aims to accelerate and de-risk drug discovery and development, including property prediction.\n\n**2. Big Pharma Companies (with internal AI capabilities and partnerships):**\n\nMajor pharmaceutical giants are investing heavily in building their own AI capabilities and collaborating with AI startups. They have the vast datasets and biological expertise to make AI predictions highly effective.\n\n*   **Pfizer:** Has been actively exploring AI for various stages of drug discovery, including target identification and property prediction.\n*   **Novartis:** Has invested in AI initiatives and partnerships to accelerate its R&D pipeline.\n*   **Roche/Genentech:** Known for their strong R&D, they are integrating AI into their drug discovery processes.\n*   **AstraZeneca:** Has been vocal about its use of AI in drug discovery, including for predicting compound properties.\n*   **Merck:** Similar to other large pharma, Merck is building internal AI expertise and forming strategic alliances.\n*   **Johnson & Johnson (Janssen):** Actively using AI and machine learning for R&D.\n\n**3. Technology Companies and Cloud Providers:**\n\nThese companies provide the underlying infrastructure, tools, and sometimes specialized AI platforms that enable drug discovery.\n\n*   **NVIDIA:** Provides powerful GPUs essential for training complex AI models and offers software platforms (like Clara Discovery) that aid in drug discovery, including property prediction.\n*   **Google (DeepMind/Google Health):** While not directly selling drug discovery services, DeepMind's work on protein folding (AlphaFold) has massive implications for understanding targets, and Google Cloud offers AI/ML tools for life sciences.\n*   **Microsoft (Azure):** Offers cloud computing and AI/ML services that are utilized by many pharma and biotech companies for their R&D efforts.\n*   **Amazon Web Services (AWS):** Provides similar cloud and AI/ML infrastructure.\n\n**4. Academic Institutions and Research Collaborations:**\n\nMany groundbreaking advancements in AI for property prediction originate from academic research. Universities often collaborate with industry partners to translate these discoveries into practical applications.\n\n**Key areas where these companies focus their AI for property prediction:**\n\n*   **Virtual Screening:** Using AI to quickly assess large libraries of compounds for their potential to bind to a target.\n*   **Lead Optimization:** Refining promising drug candidates by predicting how structural changes will affect their properties.\n*   **D